{"title_page": "Rivers Cuomo", "text_new": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Rivers Cuomo\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Rivers Cuomo Performing in 2015 - Photo by Peter Dzubay.jpg\n| image_size       = 240\n| caption          = Cuomo in 2015\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1970|6|13}}<ref>{{cite news |title= Today in history |date= 13 June 2014 |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |agency= [[Associated Press]] |accessdate= 14 June 2014 |url= http://nyti.ms/Uv1YKC}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], U.S.\n| origin           = [[Pomfret, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* {{nowrap|[[pop punk]]}}\n* [[emo]]\n* [[indie rock]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* guitarist\n}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* piano\n* keyboards\n* drums\n* harmonica<ref name=weezerpedia>https://www.weezerpedia.com/wiki/Rivers_Cuomo</ref>\n* clarinet<ref name=weezerpedia></ref>\n}}\n| years_active     = 1985\u2013present\n| label       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Geffen Records|Geffen]] \n* [[Epitaph Records|Epitaph]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n* [[Crush Management|Crush]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Weezer]]\n* [[Scott & Rivers]]\n* [[Avant Garde (band)|Avant Garde]]\n* [[Avant Garde (band)|Zoom]]\n* [[Homie (band)|Homie]]\n* [[Goat Punishment]]\n* [[Asian Kung-Fu Generation]]\n* Sixty Wrong Sausages\n* [[Steve Aoki]]\n}}\n|signature = Rivers Cuomo signature, Billboard Open Letter 2016.png\n}}\n\n'''Rivers Cuomo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|w|o\u028a|m|o\u028a}} {{respell|KWOH|moh}}; born June 13, 1970) is an American musician, singer, songwriter, and producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/hurley-mw0002031815/credits|title=Hurley - Weezer {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> He is the lead vocalist, guitarist, keyboardist, and songwriter of the rock band [[Weezer]].\n\nRaised in an [[ashram]] in [[Connecticut]] until age 10, Cuomo moved to Los Angeles at 18, where he played in several rock bands before forming Weezer in 1992. Burnt out after the success of Weezer's [[Weezer (Blue Album)|self-titled debut album]], Cuomo enrolled at [[Harvard University]] but dropped out to record Weezer's second album, [[Pinkerton (album)|''Pinkerton'']] (1996); he re-enrolled and graduated in 2008. Though ''Pinkerton'' is now frequently cited among the best albums of the 1990s and has been [[certified platinum]], it was initially a commercial and critical failure, pushing Cuomo's songwriting toward pop music.\n\nCuomo has also released three compilation albums of home demos: ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' (2007), ''[[Alone II: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' (2008) and [[Alone III: The Pinkerton Years|''Alone III: The'' Pinkerton ''Years'']] (2011). He has collaborated with a number of artists; in 2013, he and [[Scott Murphy (musician)|Scott Murphy]] released a self-titled Japanese-language album under the name [[Scott & Rivers]].\n\n== Early life ==\nRivers Cuomo was born in [[Manhattan]] to parents of [[Italian American|Italian]] and [[German American|German]]-[[English American|English]] descent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/jun/29/popandrock|title=My sporting life: Rivers Cuomo, front man of American rock band Weezer|last=Collinge|first=Miranda|date=2008-06-29|work=The Guardian|location=London}}</ref> Accounts differ as to the origin of his name. According to one account, Cuomo's mother Beverly Shoenberger named him Rivers either because he was born between [[East River|East]] and [[Hudson River|Hudson]] rivers in Manhattan or because she could hear a river outside her hospital window. However, his father, Frank Cuomo, a musician who played drums on the 1971 album ''[[Odyssey of Iska]]'' by jazz saxophonist [[Wayne Shorter]], claims Cuomo was named after three prominent soccer players.<ref name=\"page 32\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 3</ref><ref name=\"Odysseya2\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r147526|pure_url=yes}}|title=Odyssey of Iska &gt; Overview|last=Yanow|first=Scott|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2008-01-06}}</ref>\n\nRivers was raised in [[Rochester, New York]] at the [[Rochester Zen Center]], until his father left the family in 1975. His mother relocated the family to [[Yogaville]], an [[ashram]] in [[Pomfret, Connecticut]]. Cuomo attended the Pomfret Community School, and his mother married Stephen Kitts.<ref name=\"page 52\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 5</ref>\n\nIn 1980, Yogaville relocated to [[Virginia]]. The Kitts family opted to stay in Connecticut and moved to the [[Storrs, Connecticut|Storrs]] [[Mansfield, Connecticut|Mansfield]] area.<ref name=\"page 82\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 8</ref> During this time, Cuomo attended Mansfield Middle School and [[E. O. Smith High School|E.O. Smith High School]]. Rivers was a member of the high school choir and performed in a school production of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/4/26/rivers-end-the-directors-cut-the/|title=Rivers' End: The Director's Cut {{!}} Arts {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|accessdate=2015-07-20}}</ref><ref name=\"aloneroll2\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.riverspodcast.com/podcast.xml |title=Rivers 10.15 Interview with Rolling Stone |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=2008-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120115015/http://www.riverspodcast.com/podcast.xml |archivedate=2008-01-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"page 202\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 20</ref> He also changed his name to Peter Kitts;<ref name=\"page 152\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 15</ref> after graduating, Cuomo reverted to his original name.<ref name=\"page 502\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 50</ref>\n\nOne of Cuomo's earliest music projects was the [[glam metal]] band Avant Garde.<ref name=\"page 172\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 17</ref> In 1989, after playing several shows in Connecticut, Avant Garde moved to [[Los Angeles California|Los Angeles]] and changed their name to Zoom, but broke up in 1990.<ref name=\"page 312\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 31</ref><ref name=\"page 372\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 37</ref><ref name=\"page 402\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 40</ref> In 1990 and 1991, while Cuomo was writing material for what became Weezer's debut album, he was a [[roadie]] for the band King Size<ref name=\"RCFI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weezer.com/discography/RCINT2006/2006RCFI.html|title=Rivers Cuomo Fan Interview 2006|date=June 2006|publisher=Weezer.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909074200/http://www.weezer.com/discography/RCINT2006/2006RCFI.html|archivedate=9 September 2006|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> and worked at [[Tower Records (music retailer)|Tower Records]], where he listened to \"basically everything that was released at that time ... I was exposed to a ton of music I otherwise never would have heard.\"<ref name=\"RCFI2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weezer.com/discography/RCINT2006/2006RCFI.html|title=Rivers Cuomo Fan Interview 2006|date=June 2006|publisher=Weezer.com|accessdate=9 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909074200/http://www.weezer.com/discography/RCINT2006/2006RCFI.html|archivedate=9 September 2006}}</ref>\n\n== Weezer ==\n{{Main|Weezer}}Cuomo formed [[Weezer]] in 1992 with drummer [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]], bassist [[Matt Sharp]] and guitarist [[Jason Cropper]]. \"Weezer\" was the nickname given to Cuomo by his father when he was a toddler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tricycle.com/editors_pick/3546-1.html|title=Rivers in the Stream|last=Karafin|first=Amy|publisher=[[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|Tricycle]]|work=|accessdate=2007-10-15}}{{Subscription}}</ref> Weezer signed with DGC, a subsidiary of [[Geffen Records]], on June 25, 1993, and released their [[Weezer (Blue Album)|self-titled debut album]], also known as the ''Blue Album'', in May 1994. Cropper left the band during the album recording and was replaced by [[Brian Bell]]. The album was [[RIAA certification|certified]] platinum on January 1, 1995, with sales of over one million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |title=Gold and Platinum: Searchable Database |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=August 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archivedate=June 26, 2007 }}</ref> Despite his success, Cuomo tired of the monotony and loneliness of touring and developed a \"huge inferiority complex\" about rock music, saying: \"I thought my songs were really simplistic and silly, and I wanted to write complex, intense, beautiful music.\"<ref name=\":0222\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/i-songwriter-2140096|title=I, Songwriter|last=Sullivan|first=Kate|website=L.A. Weekly|access-date=2016-04-21}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rivers Cuomo in Thailand.jpg|thumb|Cuomo in 1997]]\n\nIn March 1995, Cuomo had [[Ilizarov apparatus|extensive surgery to extend his left leg]], which was 44mm shorter than the right. This involved the surgical breaking of the leg bone, followed by months of wearing a steel brace and painful [[physiotherapy]] sessions.<ref name=\":2\" /> The procedure affected his songwriting, as he would spend long periods hospitalized under the influence of painkillers.{{sfn|Luerssen|2004|pp = 148\u2013149}}\n\nAt the end of 1995, Cuomo enrolled in [[Harvard University]] to study classical composition. He told ''[[The New York Times]]'': \"The only time I could write songs was when my frozen dinner was in the microwave. The rest of the time I was doing homework.\"<ref name=\":023\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/16/garden/16weezer.html|title=Student With a Past|date=2006-02-16|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=2015-07-20|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He auditioned for the [[Harvard\u2013Radcliffe Collegium Musicum|Harvard-Radcliffe Collegium Musicum chorus]] but was not selected.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/4/26/rivers-end-the-directors-cut-the/|title=Rivers' End: The Director's Cut {{!}} Arts {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|accessdate=2015-07-20}}</ref> He became introverted and grew a beard, and wrote in his diaries how students wearing Weezer T-shirts did not recognize him.\n\nCuomo had planned Weezer's second album to be a [[rock opera]], ''[[Songs from the Black Hole]],'' but he abandoned the project as his songwriting became \"darker, more visceral and exposed, less playful.\"<ref name=\"PinkertonDeluxe\">''Pinkerton Deluxe'' liner notes</ref> Realizing he did not enjoy [[contemporary classical music]], and missing Weezer,<ref name=\":023\"/> Cuomo dropped out of Harvard two semesters before graduation.<ref name=\":023\"/> He expressed the isolation and sexual frustration he had felt at Harvard in Weezer's second album, ''[[Pinkerton (album)|Pinkerton]]'', released in September 1996. With a darker, more abrasive sound than Weezer's debut, ''Pinkerton'' was a commercial and critical failure, but attained critical acclaim later.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/pinkerton-mw0000646499|title=''Pinkerton'' \u2013 Weezer : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards : AllMusic|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|publisher=[[AllRovi]]|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the mixed response to ''Pinkerton'', Weezer went on a five-year hiatus. Cuomo enrolled at Harvard twice more and completed semesters in 1997 and 2004.<ref name=\":023\" /><ref name=\":023\" /> During the 1997 semester, he played with a new band, [[Homie (band)|Homie]], in Boston. In February 1998, Cuomo disbanded Homie and moved to Los Angeles to work on new Weezer demos with Bell and Wilson, but the sessions were unproductive. In 1998 and 1999, he lived in an apartment under a freeway in [[Culver City, California]]. In an essay for Harvard, he wrote: \"I became more and more isolated. I unplugged my phone. I painted the walls and ceiling of my bedroom black and covered the windows with fiberglass insulation.\"<ref name=\":023\" />\n\nDisappointed by ''Pinkerton''<nowiki/>'s reception, Cuomo intended to return to simpler songwriting with less personal lyrics. He stated that Weezer's subsequent albums, the ''[[Weezer (Green Album)|Green Album]]'' (2001) and ''[[Maladroit]]'' (2002)'','' were \"very intentionally not about me. Not about what was going on in my life, at least in a conscious way.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> He also developed a greater appreciation for pop music, feeling that its multiple disciplines \u2014including lyrics, improvisation, and image \u2014produce a multifaceted art \"that moves people and is important, and relevant to our culture in a way that serious classical music isn't right now.\"<ref name=\":0222\" /> In June 2006, he graduated [[cum laude]] with a Bachelor of Arts in English from Harvard<ref name=\"page 222\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 22</ref> and was elected to [[Phi Beta Kappa]].<ref name=\"autogenerated32\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.spin.com/2006/06/rivers-cuomos-harvard-graduation/|title=Rivers Cuomo's Harvard Graduation|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=2007-10-15}}</ref>\n\nOn December 6, 2009, Cuomo was in his tour bus driving to [[Boston]] from [[Toronto]] with his family and assistant when the bus hit an icy road in [[Glen, New York]] and crashed. He suffered cracked ribs and internal bleeding. Weezer canceled the rest of the 2009 tour dates, planning to reschedule them the following year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Music/12/06/weezer.accident/|title=Weezer singer hurt in bus crash - CNN.com|date=2009-12-07|work=CNN|accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref> The band made its return to the stage on January 20, 2010, performing at [[Florida State University]] in [[Tallahassee, Florida]].\n\n==Other projects==\n[[File:Rivers Cuomo 2009-no watermark.jpg|thumb|left|Cuomo performing in 2009]]\nDuring Weezer's hiatus after the release of ''Pinkerton'', Cuomo formed [[Homie (band)|Homie]], and performed what he called \"goofball songs\" for his \"country band\". An album was planned, but only one studio recording, a song titled \"American Girls\", was released. Cuomo has contributed to recordings by various other musicians ([[Crazy Town]], [[Cold (band)|Cold]], [[Mark Ronson]]). Cuomo managed the band [[AM Radio (band)|AM Radio]] in 2002 and 2003; he and the band's frontman, [[Kevin Ridel]], went to school together.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1473358/weezers-rivers-cuomo-helps-am-radio-dress-for-success/|title=Weezer's Rivers Cuomo Helps AM Radio Dress For Success|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2004, Cuomo joined ex-Weezer bassist [[Matt Sharp]] onstage [[California State University, Fullerton]]. They worked on a record together in February that month, but the material remains unreleased.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1491398/matt-sharp-says-lp-with-rivers-cuomo-may-never-come-out/|title=Matt Sharp Says LP With Rivers Cuomo May Never Come Out|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> In March 2008, Cuomo began a YouTube video series in which he wrote a song in collaboration with YouTube viewers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/28935-help-rivers-cuomo-write-a-new-sawng/|title=Help Rivers Cuomo Write a New \"Sawng\"! {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> The finished song, \"Turning Up the Radio\", was released in 2010 on the Weezer compilation album ''[[Death to False Metal]]''.<ref name=\"Cohen-Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last1=Cohen|first1=Ian|title=Weezer: Death to False Metal|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14817-weezer-pinkerton-deluxe-edition-death-to-false-metal/|website=pitchfork.com|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, Cuomo released ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'', a compilation of his demos recorded from 1992 to 2007.<ref name=\"drown\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.drownedinsound.com/articles/2494715|title=Weezer's Rivers Cuomo to release solo album|last=Kharas|first=Kev|magazine=[[Drowned in Sound]]|accessdate=October 16, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017051234/http://drownedinsound.com/articles/2494715|archivedate=October 17, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> It was followed by ''[[Alone II: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' in November 2008<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/33865-rivers-cuomo-talks-alone-ii-weezer-that-hair/|title=Rivers Cuomo Talks Alone II, Weezer, That Hair|last=Thompson|first=Paul|date=October 28, 2007|website=|publisher=Pitchfork Media|accessdate=July 13, 2014}}</ref> and ''[[Alone III: The Pinkerton Years]]'' in November 2010; the latter album was sold exclusively with a book, ''The Pinkerton Diaries'', which collects Cuomo's writings from the preceding the release of ''Pinkerton''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/44605-rivers-cuomo-releasing-pinkerton-diaries-book-and-demos-comp-alone-iii/|title=Rivers Cuomo Releasing Pinkerton Diaries Book and Demos Comp Alone III|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=November 11, 2011|website=|publisher=Pitchfork Media|accessdate=July 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCuomo has made [[cameo appearance|cameos]] in a number of music videos. These include [[The Crystal Method]]'s \"Murder\" and the video for [[The Warlocks]]' \"Cocaine Blues.\" Cuomo also makes a guest appearance on [[Sugar Ray]]'s \"Boardwalk\", the first single on the group's latest album, ''[[Music for Cougars]]''. Cuomo featured on the song \"[[Magic (B.o.B song)|Magic]]\", on [[B.o.B]]'s debut album ''[[B.o.B Presents: The Adventures of Bobby Ray]]'' which was released in April 2010. In a May interview with [[HitQuarters]], producer-songwriter [[Lucas Secon]] confirmed that he had recently worked with Cuomo on both a [[Steve Aoki]] single and \"some Weezer stuff.\"<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_Lucas_Secon_Interview.html |title=Interview With Lucas Secon |publisher=[[HitQuarters]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=May 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314062111/http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview%2Fopar%2Fintrview_Lucas_Secon_Interview.html |archivedate=March 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Cuomo collaborated with Japanese singer Hitomi for her first [[independent music|independent]] album ''[[Spirit (Hitomi album)|Spirit]]'', in the duet \"Rollin' with da Homies\", co-written by him. He was also featured on the [[Simple Plan]] song \"[[Can't Keep My Hands Off You]]\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Newman|first=Jason|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2011/03/31/simple-plan-rivers-cuomo-cant-keep-my-hands-off-you/|title=New Song: Simple Plan With Rivers Cuomo, 'Can't Keep My Hands Off You'|publisher=MTV|date=March 11, 2011|accessdate=January 27, 2013}}</ref> and [[Miranda Cosgrove]]'s song, \"High Maintenance\".<ref name=\"Graff-Billboard\">{{cite web|last1=Graff|first1=Gary|title=Miranda Cosgrove Taps Rivers Cuomo for 'High Maintenance' Duet|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473348/miranda-cosgrove-taps-rivers-cuomo-for-high-maintenance-duet|website=Billboard|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> In 2013, Cuomo released a self-titled Japanese-language album with [[Scott Murphy (musician)|Scott Murphy]] of the band [[Allister]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=2123462|title=Allister News |website=[[AbsolutePunk]]|date=January 13, 2011 |accessdate=January 14, 2011}}</ref> under the name [[Scott & Rivers]]. The album debuted at #1 on the iTunes Japan alternative charts. The album was released physically in Japan and digitally worldwide through [[iTunes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/scott-rivers/id633593815 |title=iTunes - Music - Scott & Rivers by Scott & Rivers |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2013-03-20 |accessdate=2015-07-25}}</ref> In 2015, Cuomo appeared on the song \"Snowed In\" on [[Big Data (band)|Big Data's]] album ''[[2.0 (Big Data album)|2.0]]''.<ref name=\"Minsker-pf\">{{cite web|last1=Minsker|first1=Evan|title=Rivers Cuomo Teams With Big Data for \"Snowed In\"|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/58373-rivers-cuomo-teams-with-big-data-for-snowed-in/|website=pitchfork.com|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> In the same year, Cuomo produced a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] pilot for a sitcom based on his life, ''DeTour'', starring [[Ben Aldridge (actor)|Ben Aldridge]] as Cuomo. The pilot was not picked up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/07/tv-sitcom-about-rivers-cuomos-life-will-never-air/|title=TV sitcom about Rivers Cuomo's life will never air|date=2015-07-10|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Cuomo featured in RAC's \"I Still Wanna Know\", as well as Vic Mensa's \"Homewrecker\", which sampled Weezer's \"The Good Life\". The same year, he co-wrote and appeared on [[AJR (band)|AJR]]'s \"[[Sober Up]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weatherby|first1=Taylor|title=AJR Unveils 'Sober Up' Collaboration With Their Hero, Weezer's Rivers Cuomo: Premiere|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7824823/ajr-new-song-sober-up-rivers-cuomo-weezer-the-click|website=Billboard|accessdate=7 May 2018|date=6 August 2017}}</ref>  Cuomo also co-wrote the song \"Why Won't You Love Me\" on [[5 Seconds of Summer]]'s 2018 album [[Youngblood (5 Seconds of Summer album)|Youngblood]]. In 2018, he helped write two songs, \"Clock Work\" and \"Dancing Girl\" for [[Asian Kung-Fu Generation]]'s 2018 album, [[Hometown (Asian Kung-Fu Generation album)|Hometown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moshimoshi-nippon.jp/148583 |title=\nMMN Interview (Part 1): ASIAN KUNG-FU GENERATION discuss how writing 'Home Town' was different from their previous records |publisher=Moshi Moshi Nippon|date=2018-11-29 |accessdate=2018-11-29}}</ref> In 2019, he wrote and performed \"Backflip,\" the theme song for the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Green Eggs and Ham (TV series)|Green Eggs and Ham]]''.<ref>{{citeweb|last1=Ginsberg|first1=Gab|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8541553/rivers-cuomo-backflip-netflix-green-eggs-ham|title=Get a First Listen Of Rivers Cuomo's 'Backflip' Theme Song For Netflix's 'Green Eggs and Ham': Exclusive|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 31, 2019|accessdate=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n[[File:Weezer River Cuomo Bethlehem 2019 1.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Rivers Cuomo performing with Weezer at [[Musikfest]] in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]], [[Pennsylvania]] on August 5, 2019.]]\nAppearing on the [[Song Exploder]] podcast in 2016, Cuomo explained the process he used to write albums such as Weezer's ''[[Weezer (White Album)|White Album]]'' (2016). He maintains [[Spotify]] playlists of music with \"cool\" chord progressions that he uses to find musical inspiration. He sometimes uses piano to write vocal melodies his vocal muscles would be \"too lazy\" to create. Conversely, he improvises vocal melodies to write guitar solos, to avoid guitar habits and create solos \"you can sing along to\" with \"space in [them] because I have to breathe\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTo write lyrics, Cuomo writes [[Stream of consciousness (narrative mode)|stream-of-consciousness]] thoughts in his journal, then highlights interesting lines and adds them to a spreadsheet of potential lyrics organized by number of syllables and [[Stress (linguistics)|strong-weak emphasis]]. When he comes to write a song, he finds lines that fit the melody and assembles them in a way that suggests a story.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2016/04/rivers-cuomo-weezer-summer-elaine-drunk-dori-song-exploder-podcast-stream/|title=Rivers Cuomo Explains His 'Crazy Way to Write' Tracks on 'Song Exploder' {{!}} SPIN|website=Spin|access-date=2016-04-20}}</ref> He rarely uses [[profanity]] in his lyrics, as \"Weezer came up at a time when [[Jane's Addiction]] released ''[[Nothing's Shocking]]''\u2014everyone was trying to be controversial. We looked back to rock and roll's pre-drug days\u2014to the clean images of the Beach Boys\u2014that felt, ironically, rebellious.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/rivers-cuomo-20080626|title=Q&A: Rivers Cuomo|last=Scaggs|first=Austin|date=2008-06-28|magazine=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2015-05-03}}</ref> He has experimented with various methods of \"concentration\", such as [[fasting]], to aid his songwriting.<ref name=\":0222\" />\n\n=== Influences ===\nCuomo credited the [[The Beach Boys|Beach Boys]] as a major influence on his early songwriting, and told ''Upset'' magazine:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.upsetmagazine.com/features/weezer-interview-kings-of-the-world-white-album/|title=Weezer: Kings of the world {{!}} Interview {{!}} Upset|date=2016-05-06|language=en-US|access-date=2016-07-31}}</ref>{{cquote|I remember when I was 21 or 22, right when Weezer got together. I went to the local used record shop in Santa Monica with the intention of buying a classic album that was going to be a huge influence on me and my writing for Weezer. I flipped through all the records and I narrowed it down to two records. One of them was [[Led Zeppelin (album)|''Led Zeppelin'']], the other was ''[[Pet Sounds]]'' by the Beach Boys. It was almost a coin toss but I ended up going with ''Pet Sounds'', and I really came to love the melodies and the chord progression and the emotion on that record. It has to be one of the biggest influences right when Weezer was starting out.}}\n\nOn tour with Weezer following the ''Blue Album'', Cuomo listened extensively to the operas ''[[Aida]]'' (1871) and ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' (1904), the rock opera ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]'' (1970), and the musical ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]'' (1980), which influenced the composition of ''Pinkerton'' and the unreleased ''[[Songs from the Black Hole]].''<ref name=\"AloneII\">''Alone II: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo'' (liner notes). Rivers Cuomo. DGC, Interscope Records. 2008. B0012341-02</ref>\n\nOther influences include the [[the Beatles|Beatles]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Giacomo Puccini]], [[Green Day]], [[Jane's Addiction]], [[Cat Stevens]], [[Lou Barlow]], [[The Who]], [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]], [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]] and [[Sonic Youth]]. In the late 90s, Cuomo created an \"Encyclopedia of Pop\" for himself, a three-ring binder which examined pop and rock songs by artists including Nirvana, Green Day and [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]].<ref name=\"ELISCU\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5933454/rivers_cuomos_encyclopedia_of_pop|title=Rivers Cuomo's Encyclopedia of Pop|last=Eliscu|first=Jenny|magazine=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2007-10-15}}</ref><ref name=\"page 270\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 270</ref> In 2008, he said his biggest recent inspiration had been [[Eminem]], praising his \"creativity, passion, inventiveness, and playfulness\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/interview/6773-rivers-cuomo/|title=Rivers Cuomo {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Voice ===\nCuomo possesses the vocal range of a tenor.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Kilby |first=Dylan |url= http://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/weezer-everything-will-alright-end |title= Weezer \u2013 Everything Will Be Alright In The End |date= 6 October 2014|accessdate= 16 January 2015 |magazine=musicOMH}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.axs.com/guy-grogan-channels-elliot-smith-and-rivers-cuomo-on-dynamite-bouquet-79926| title = Guy Grogan channels Elliot Smith and Rivers Cuomo on 'Dynamite Bouquet'| work=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|date=29 March 2016|accessdate=13 May 2018| first=MacEagon| last=Voyce}}</ref><ref name=\"News\">{{cite news| url = http://www.newsadvance.com/the_burg/music/review-weezer-s-rivers-cuomo-has-reverse-engineered-a-really/article_1f7fca2b-8fc3-53b6-a5ac-a0be1bd1d18d.html| title = Review: Weezer's Rivers Cuomo has reverse engineered a really good album| work=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|date=17 August 2016|accessdate=13 May 2018| first=Matt| last=Ashare}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://badgerherald.com/artsetc/2016/04/06/weezers-new-album-is-sonically-brilliant-but-lyrically-flawed/| title = Weezer's new album is sonically brilliant, but lyrically flawed| work=[[The Badger Herald]]|date=6 April 2016|accessdate=13 May 2018| first=Aaron| last=Reilly}}</ref> Matt Ashare of ''[[The News & Advance]]'' describes his voice as \"refreshingly pleasant\".<ref name=\"News\"/>\n\n==Equipment==\n[[Weezer (Blue Album)|The Blue Album]] was recorded with a [[Gibson Les Paul Special]] and a [[Fender Jaguar]], borrowed from producer [[Ric Ocasek]]. His amp was a vintage Mesa Boogie Mark I. For touring, he initially used a sonic blue Warmoth [[Fender Stratocaster]] copy with Seymour Duncan and DiMarzio pickups alongside Marshall amps. However, the guitar was destroyed in late 1997. In recent years, he has used additional Warmoth strat copies (in blue, seafoam green, black and blonde), as well as a [[Gibson SG]] painted in white with stock pickups. The guitars are plugged into a Kemper Profiler amp.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/rig-tour-weezer|title=Rig tour: Weezer|last=Sharma|first=Amit|publisher=MusicRadar|accessdate=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCuomo took a vow of [[sexual abstinence]] from 2004 until his marriage in 2006.<ref name=\":023\"/> On June 18, 2006, Cuomo married Kyoko Ito, whom he met in March 1997 at one of his solo concerts at the [[The Middle East (nightclub)|Middle East Club]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/4/26/rivers-end-in-early-1995-a/|title=Rivers' End|last=Riesman|first=Abe J.|date=April 26, 2006|work=The Harvard Crimson}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Edwards|first=Gavin|date=November 12, 2009|title=Rivers Cuomo Grows Up (But Don't Worry, He's Still Kinda Weird)|journal=Rolling Stone|volume=|pages=60\u201363}}</ref> He proposed to her in Tokyo shortly before Christmas 2005.<ref name=\"HarvardCrim\">{{cite news |last=Chen |first=Lena |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=511290 |title=Hey, Rivers Cuomo! What did you do for Valentine's Day? |newspaper=[[The Harvard Crimson]] |date=2006-12-21 |accessdate=2007-10-17}}</ref> The wedding was held at a beach on Paradise Cove in [[Malibu, California|Malibu]] and was attended by all past and present members of Weezer (except for [[Mikey Welsh]]), as well as [[Kevin Ridel]] of [[Ridel High]] and [[Rick Rubin]].<ref name=shon>{{cite web|title=Full story|url=http://weezer.com/community/news_comment.asp?ParentAssetID=1455490&ArtistID=479&Start=&FullStory=Y&type=|publisher=Weezer.com|accessdate=9 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061129191804/http://www.weezer.com/community/news_comment.asp?ParentAssetID=1455490&ArtistID=479&Start=&FullStory=Y&type=|archivedate=29 November 2006}}</ref> The couple have two children: daughter Mia, born in 2007, and son Leo, born in 2011.\n\nCuomo was born with his [[Unequal leg length|left leg nearly two inches shorter than his right]]. After the success of ''[[Weezer (Blue Album)|The Blue Album]]'', Cuomo underwent the [[Ilizarov apparatus|Ilizarov procedure]] to correct the condition. This involved the surgical breaking of the bone in his leg, followed by several months of wearing a steel brace which required self-administered \"stretching\" of the leg four times daily; Cuomo likened the ordeal to \"crucifying [his] leg.\"<ref name=\":2\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 148\u2013149</ref>\n\nCuomo has been vegetarian since childhood.<ref name=\"Rivers Cuomo Vegetarian\">{{cite web | url=http://www.happycow.net/famous/rivers_cuomo/|title=Rivers Cuomo Vegetarian |accessdate=2008-07-03 |publisher=Happycow.net}}</ref><ref name=\"Rivers 2002 Interview\">{{cite web|url=http://thebadpennyblog.com/2010/09/17/weezers-rivers-cuomo-in-2002-i-think-i-had-a-falling-out-with-the-fans/ |title=Weezer's Rivers Cuomo In 2002: 'I Think I Had A Falling Out With The Fans'|publisher=Thebadpennyblog.com |date=2010-09-17 |accessdate=2015-07-25}}</ref> However, in 2002, he told an interviewer that he might like to start eating meat regularly and claimed to have done so in the past, eating \"some kind of barbecued beef in Tokyo.\"<ref name=\"Rivers 2002 Interview\" />\n\nCuomo practices [[Vipassan\u0101]] [[meditation]] and was a student of [[S. N. Goenka]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.shambhalasun.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2850&Itemid=0 |title=Lion's Roar - Buddhist Wisdom for Our Time |publisher=Shambhalasun.com |date= |accessdate=2015-07-25}}</ref> As of mid-2009 he also teaches children's meditation as taught by S. N. Goenka.<ref>[http://www.vridhamma.org/en2009-08.aspx] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100713220221/http://www.vridhamma.org/en2009-08.aspx|date=July 13, 2010}}</ref> Cuomo helped acquire music rights and provided financial support to a 2007 documentary titled ''[[The Dhamma Brothers]]'' about [[Vipassan\u0101]] meditation being instituted in an Alabama state prison.<ref name=\"DBros\">{{cite web|url=http://www.frizzylogic.org/fl/2007/07/11/the-dhamma-brothers/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224182903/http://www.frizzylogic.org/fl/2007/07/11/the-dhamma-brothers/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-12-24 |title=The Dhamma Brothers |publisher=Frizzy Logic |accessdate=2007-10-15 }}</ref>\n\nCuomo is not a soccer fan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://riverscuomo.com/bio/|title=Bio|date=2011-05-11|work=The Official Site of Rivers Cuomo -|access-date=2017-03-16|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2006, he wrote a song, \"My Day Is Coming\", in tribute to the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. men's soccer team]], and in 2010 wrote \"Represent\", an \"unofficial anthem\" for the U.S. team released as a Weezer single on June 11, the day before Team USA's [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group C#England vs United States|World Cup opener]] against [[England national football team|England]].<ref name=\"Represent\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1641349/20100611/weezer.jhtml |title=Weezer Debut 'Unofficial' World Cup Song, 'Represent' |first=James |last=Montgomery |publisher=MTV.com |date=June 11, 2010 |accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref> In early 2008, Cuomo played in the [[Mia Hamm|Mia]] & [[Nomar Garciaparra|Nomar]] Celebrity Soccer Challenge and scored a goal in the game. The video for \"Lover in the Snow\", from the ''Alone'' album, deals with this game and his love of soccer.<ref name=\"Represent\" /> In August 2009, Cuomo participated in the Athletes for Africa 5v5 Charity Soccer Tournament in Toronto, Canada alongside actor [[Michael Cera]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/actor-takes-part-in-charity-soccer-tournament-today/article1201621/|title=Actor takes part in charity soccer tournament today|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Rafton|first=Robert|title=5v5 (7)|date=2009-08-22|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/rafton/3852145725/|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref>\n\nCuomo performed at a campaign rally for Democratic Presidential candidate [[Andrew Yang 2020 presidential campaign|Andrew Yang]] in Iowa on November 1, 2019, though Cuomo did not explicitly endorse Yang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/11/rivers-cuomo-performs-weezer-songs-at-andrew-yang-yangapalooza-watch/|title=Here's Rivers Cuomo Performing at an Andrew Yang Rally in Iowa|date=2019-11-02|website=Spin|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/heres-what-happened-during-rivers-cuomos-yangapalooza-set/|title=Here\u2019s What Happened During Rivers Cuomo\u2019s Set at the Andrew Yang Rally in Iowa|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Rivers Cuomo discography}}\n\n'''With Weezer'''\n* [[Weezer (Blue Album)|''Blue Album'']] (1994)\n* [[Pinkerton (album)|''Pinkerton'']] (1996)\n* [[Weezer (Green Album)|''Green Album'']] (2001)\n* ''[[Maladroit]]'' (2002)\n* [[Make Believe (Weezer album)|''Make Believe'']] (2005)\n* [[Weezer (Red Album)|''Red Album'']] (2008)\n* ''[[Raditude]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Hurley (album)|Hurley]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Death to False Metal]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Everything Will Be Alright in the End]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Weezer (White Album)|White Album]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Pacific Daydream]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Weezer (Teal Album)|Teal Album]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Weezer (Black Album)|Black Album]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Van Weezer]]'' (2020)\n\n'''Solo''' \n* ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Alone II: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Not Alone \u2013 Rivers Cuomo and Friends: Live at Fingerprints]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Alone III: The Pinkerton Years]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Scott & Rivers]]'' (2013)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=513079 Interview with The Harvard Crimson about his Harvard years]\n* {{musicbrainz artist|name=Rivers Cuomo|id=87b6344f-c874-49ce-a8b3-e467ed6e05d0}}\n* {{IMDb name|1220530|Rivers Cuomo}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071223012636/http://community.livejournal.com/rivers_words/ Rivers Cuomo Archived MySpace Postings]\n* [http://goinginanewdirection.tripod.com/id10.html Rivers Cuomo on his creative career]\n* [http://www.shambhalasun.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2850&Itemid=0 Biographical article in Shambhala Sun Magazine]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/ScottAndRivers/ Scott & Rivers on Facebook]\n\n{{Rivers Cuomo}}\n{{Weezer}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuomo, Rivers}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:Berklee College of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singers from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Singers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Weezer members]]\n[[Category:Musicians Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Power pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Connecticut]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Rivers Cuomo\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = Rivers Cuomo Performing in 2015 - Photo by Peter Dzubay.jpg\n| image_size       = 240\n| caption          = Cuomo in 2015\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1970|6|13}}<ref>{{cite news |title= Today in history |date= 13 June 2014 |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |agency= [[Associated Press]] |accessdate= 14 June 2014 |url= http://nyti.ms/Uv1YKC}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Manhattan]], [[New York City]], U.S.\n| origin           = [[Pomfret, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[power pop]]\n* {{nowrap|[[pop punk]]}}\n* [[emo]]\n* [[indie rock]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* guitarist\n}}\n| instrument       = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n* piano\n* keyboards\n* drums\n* harmonica<ref name=weezerpedia>https://www.weezerpedia.com/wiki/Rivers_Cuomo</ref>\n* clarinet<ref name=weezerpedia></ref>\n}}\n| years_active     = 1985\u2013present\n| label       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Geffen Records|Geffen]] \n* [[Epitaph Records|Epitaph]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n* [[Crush Management|Crush]]\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n* [[Weezer]]\n* [[Scott & Rivers]]\n* [[Avant Garde (band)|Avant Garde]]\n* [[Avant Garde (band)|Zoom]]\n* [[Homie (band)|Homie]]\n* [[Goat Punishment]]\n* [[Asian Kung-Fu Generation]]\n* Sixty Wrong Sausages\n* [[Steve Aoki]]\n}}\n|signature = Rivers Cuomo signature, Billboard Open Letter 2016.png\n}}\n\n'''Rivers Cuomo''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|w|o\u028a|m|o\u028a}} {{respell|KWOH|moh}}; born June 13, 1970) is an American musician, singer, songwriter, and producer.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/hurley-mw0002031815/credits|title=Hurley - Weezer {{!}} Credits|website=AllMusic|language=en-us|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> He is the lead vocalist, guitarist, keyboardist, and songwriter of the rock band [[Weezer]].\n\nRaised in an [[ashram]] in [[Connecticut]] until age 10, Cuomo moved to Los Angeles at 18, where he played in several rock bands before forming Weezer in 1992. Burnt out after the success of Weezer's [[Weezer (Blue Album)|self-titled debut album]], Cuomo enrolled at [[Harvard University]] but dropped out to record Weezer's second album, [[Pinkerton (album)|''Pinkerton'']] (1996); he re-enrolled and graduated in 2008. Though ''Pinkerton'' is now frequently cited among the best albums of the 1990s and has been [[certified platinum]], it was initially a commercial and critical failure, pushing Cuomo's songwriting toward pop music.\n\nCuomo has also released three compilation albums of home demos: ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' (2007), ''[[Alone II: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' (2008) and [[Alone III: The Pinkerton Years|''Alone III: The'' Pinkerton ''Years'']] (2011). He has collaborated with a number of artists; in 2013, he and [[Scott Murphy (musician)|Scott Murphy]] released a self-titled Japanese-language album under the name [[Scott & Rivers]].\n\n== Early life ==\nRivers Cuomo was born in [[Manhattan]] to parents of [[Italian American|Italian]] and [[German American|German]]-[[English American|English]] descent.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/jun/29/popandrock|title=My sporting life: Rivers Cuomo, front man of American rock band Weezer|last=Collinge|first=Miranda|date=2008-06-29|work=The Guardian|location=London}}</ref> Accounts differ as to the origin of his name. According to one account, Cuomo's mother Beverly Shoenberger named him Rivers either because he was born between [[East River|East]] and [[Hudson River|Hudson]] rivers in Manhattan or because she could hear a river outside her hospital window. However, his father, Frank Cuomo, a musician who played drums on the 1971 album ''[[Odyssey of Iska]]'' by jazz saxophonist [[Wayne Shorter]], claims Cuomo was named after three prominent soccer players.<ref name=\"page 32\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 3</ref><ref name=\"Odysseya2\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r147526|pure_url=yes}}|title=Odyssey of Iska &gt; Overview|last=Yanow|first=Scott|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2008-01-06}}</ref>\n\nRivers was raised in [[Rochester, New York]] at the [[Rochester Zen Center]], until his father left the family in 1975. His mother relocated the family to [[Yogaville]], an [[ashram]] in [[Pomfret, Connecticut]]. Cuomo attended the Pomfret Community School, and his mother married Stephen Kitts.<ref name=\"page 52\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 5</ref>\n\nIn 1980, Yogaville relocated to [[Virginia]]. The Kitts family opted to stay in Connecticut and moved to the [[Storrs, Connecticut|Storrs]] [[Mansfield, Connecticut|Mansfield]] area.<ref name=\"page 82\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 8</ref> During this time, Cuomo attended Mansfield Middle School and [[E. O. Smith High School|E.O. Smith High School]]. Rivers was a member of the high school choir and performed in a school production of ''[[Grease (musical)|Grease]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/4/26/rivers-end-the-directors-cut-the/|title=Rivers' End: The Director's Cut {{!}} Arts {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|accessdate=2015-07-20}}</ref><ref name=\"aloneroll2\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.riverspodcast.com/podcast.xml |title=Rivers 10.15 Interview with Rolling Stone |magazine=Rolling Stone |accessdate=2008-01-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120115015/http://www.riverspodcast.com/podcast.xml |archivedate=2008-01-20 }}</ref><ref name=\"page 202\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 20</ref> He also changed his name to Peter Kitts;<ref name=\"page 152\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 15</ref> after graduating, Cuomo reverted to his original name.<ref name=\"page 502\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 50</ref>\n\nOne of Cuomo's earliest music projects was the [[glam metal]] band Avant Garde.<ref name=\"page 172\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 17</ref> In 1989, after playing several shows in Connecticut, Avant Garde moved to [[Los Angeles California|Los Angeles]] and changed their name to Zoom, but broke up in 1990.<ref name=\"page 312\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 31</ref><ref name=\"page 372\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 37</ref><ref name=\"page 402\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 40</ref> In 1990 and 1991, while Cuomo was writing material for what became Weezer's debut album, he was a [[roadie]] for the band King Size<ref name=\"RCFI\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weezer.com/discography/RCINT2006/2006RCFI.html|title=Rivers Cuomo Fan Interview 2006|date=June 2006|publisher=Weezer.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909074200/http://www.weezer.com/discography/RCINT2006/2006RCFI.html|archivedate=9 September 2006|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> and worked at [[Tower Records (music retailer)|Tower Records]], where he listened to \"basically everything that was released at that time ... I was exposed to a ton of music I otherwise never would have heard.\"<ref name=\"RCFI2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.weezer.com/discography/RCINT2006/2006RCFI.html|title=Rivers Cuomo Fan Interview 2006|date=June 2006|publisher=Weezer.com|accessdate=9 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909074200/http://www.weezer.com/discography/RCINT2006/2006RCFI.html|archivedate=9 September 2006}}</ref>\n\n== Weezer ==\n{{Main|Weezer}}Cuomo formed [[Weezer]] in 1992 with drummer [[Patrick Wilson (musician)|Patrick Wilson]], bassist [[Matt Sharp]] and guitarist [[Jason Cropper]]. \"Weezer\" was the nickname given to Cuomo by his father when he was a toddler.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tricycle.com/editors_pick/3546-1.html|title=Rivers in the Stream|last=Karafin|first=Amy|publisher=[[Tricycle: The Buddhist Review|Tricycle]]|work=|accessdate=2007-10-15}}{{Subscription}}</ref> Weezer signed with DGC, a subsidiary of [[Geffen Records]], on June 25, 1993, and released their [[Weezer (Blue Album)|self-titled debut album]], also known as the ''Blue Album'', in May 1994. Cropper left the band during the album recording and was replaced by [[Brian Bell]]. The album was [[RIAA certification|certified]] platinum on January 1, 1995, with sales of over one million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |title=Gold and Platinum: Searchable Database |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=August 30, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH |archivedate=June 26, 2007 }}</ref> Despite his success, Cuomo tired of the monotony and loneliness of touring and developed a \"huge inferiority complex\" about rock music, saying: \"I thought my songs were really simplistic and silly, and I wanted to write complex, intense, beautiful music.\"<ref name=\":0222\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/i-songwriter-2140096|title=I, Songwriter|last=Sullivan|first=Kate|website=L.A. Weekly|access-date=2016-04-21}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Rivers Cuomo in Thailand.jpg|thumb|Cuomo in 1997]]\n\nIn March 1995, Cuomo had [[Ilizarov apparatus|extensive surgery to extend his left leg]], which was 44mm shorter than the right. This involved the surgical breaking of the leg bone, followed by months of wearing a steel brace and painful [[physiotherapy]] sessions.<ref name=\":2\" /> The procedure affected his songwriting, as he would spend long periods hospitalized under the influence of painkillers.{{sfn|Luerssen|2004|pp = 148\u2013149}}\n\nAt the end of 1995, Cuomo enrolled in [[Harvard University]] to study classical composition. He told ''[[The New York Times]]'': \"The only time I could write songs was when my frozen dinner was in the microwave. The rest of the time I was doing homework.\"<ref name=\":023\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/02/16/garden/16weezer.html|title=Student With a Past|date=2006-02-16|newspaper=The New York Times|access-date=2015-07-20|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He auditioned for the [[Harvard\u2013Radcliffe Collegium Musicum|Harvard-Radcliffe Collegium Musicum chorus]] but was not selected.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/4/26/rivers-end-the-directors-cut-the/|title=Rivers' End: The Director's Cut {{!}} Arts {{!}} The Harvard Crimson|website=www.thecrimson.com|accessdate=2015-07-20}}</ref> He became introverted and grew a beard, and wrote in his diaries how students wearing Weezer T-shirts did not recognize him.\n\nCuomo had planned Weezer's second album to be a [[rock opera]], ''[[Songs from the Black Hole]],'' but he abandoned the project as his songwriting became \"darker, more visceral and exposed, less playful.\"<ref name=\"PinkertonDeluxe\">''Pinkerton Deluxe'' liner notes</ref> Realizing he did not enjoy [[contemporary classical music]], and missing Weezer,<ref name=\":023\"/> Cuomo dropped out of Harvard two semesters before graduation.<ref name=\":023\"/> He expressed the isolation and sexual frustration he had felt at Harvard in Weezer's second album, ''[[Pinkerton (album)|Pinkerton]]'', released in September 1996. With a darker, more abrasive sound than Weezer's debut, ''Pinkerton'' was a commercial and critical failure, but attained critical acclaim later.<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/pinkerton-mw0000646499|title=''Pinkerton'' \u2013 Weezer : Songs, Reviews, Credits, Awards : AllMusic|last=Erlewine|first=Stephen Thomas|authorlink=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|publisher=[[AllRovi]]|work=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=June 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the mixed response to ''Pinkerton'', Weezer went on a five-year hiatus. Cuomo enrolled at Harvard twice more and completed semesters in 1997 and 2004.<ref name=\":023\" /><ref name=\":023\" /> During the 1997 semester, he played with a new band, [[Homie (band)|Homie]], in Boston. In February 1998, Cuomo disbanded Homie and moved to Los Angeles to work on new Weezer demos with Bell and Wilson, but the sessions were unproductive. In 1998 and 1999, he lived in an apartment under a freeway in [[Culver City, California]]. In an essay for Harvard, he wrote: \"I became more and more isolated. I unplugged my phone. I painted the walls and ceiling of my bedroom black and covered the windows with fiberglass insulation.\"<ref name=\":023\" />\n\nDisappointed by ''Pinkerton''<nowiki/>'s reception, Cuomo intended to return to simpler songwriting with less personal lyrics. He stated that Weezer's subsequent albums, the ''[[Weezer (Green Album)|Green Album]]'' (2001) and ''[[Maladroit]]'' (2002)'','' were \"very intentionally not about me. Not about what was going on in my life, at least in a conscious way.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> He also developed a greater appreciation for pop music, feeling that its multiple disciplines \u2014including lyrics, improvisation, and image \u2014produce a multifaceted art \"that moves people and is important, and relevant to our culture in a way that serious classical music isn't right now.\"<ref name=\":0222\" /> In June 2006, he graduated [[cum laude]] with a Bachelor of Arts in English from Harvard<ref name=\"page 222\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 22</ref> and was elected to [[Phi Beta Kappa]].<ref name=\"autogenerated32\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.spin.com/2006/06/rivers-cuomos-harvard-graduation/|title=Rivers Cuomo's Harvard Graduation|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|accessdate=2007-10-15}}</ref>\n\nOn December 6, 2009, Cuomo was in his tour bus driving to [[Boston]] from [[Toronto]] with his family and assistant when the bus hit an icy road in [[Glen, New York]] and crashed. He suffered cracked ribs and internal bleeding. Weezer canceled the rest of the 2009 tour dates, planning to reschedule them the following year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/SHOWBIZ/Music/12/06/weezer.accident/|title=Weezer singer hurt in bus crash - CNN.com|date=2009-12-07|work=CNN|accessdate=2010-05-22}}</ref> The band made its return to the stage on January 20, 2010, performing at [[Florida State University]] in [[Tallahassee, Florida]].\n\n==Other projects==\n[[File:Rivers Cuomo 2009-no watermark.jpg|thumb|left|Cuomo performing in 2009]]\nDuring Weezer's hiatus after the release of ''Pinkerton'', Cuomo formed [[Homie (band)|Homie]], and performed what he called \"goofball songs\" for his \"country band\". An album was planned, but only one studio recording, a song titled \"American Girls\", was released. Cuomo has contributed to recordings by various other musicians ([[Crazy Town]], [[Cold (band)|Cold]], [[Mark Ronson]]). Cuomo managed the band [[AM Radio (band)|AM Radio]] in 2002 and 2003; he and the band's frontman, [[Kevin Ridel]], went to school together.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1473358/weezers-rivers-cuomo-helps-am-radio-dress-for-success/|title=Weezer's Rivers Cuomo Helps AM Radio Dress For Success|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2004, Cuomo joined ex-Weezer bassist [[Matt Sharp]] onstage [[California State University, Fullerton]]. They worked on a record together in February that month, but the material remains unreleased.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1491398/matt-sharp-says-lp-with-rivers-cuomo-may-never-come-out/|title=Matt Sharp Says LP With Rivers Cuomo May Never Come Out|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> In March 2008, Cuomo began a YouTube video series in which he wrote a song in collaboration with YouTube viewers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/28935-help-rivers-cuomo-write-a-new-sawng/|title=Help Rivers Cuomo Write a New \"Sawng\"! {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref> The finished song, \"Turning Up the Radio\", was released in 2010 on the Weezer compilation album ''[[Death to False Metal]]''.<ref name=\"Cohen-Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last1=Cohen|first1=Ian|title=Weezer: Death to False Metal|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/14817-weezer-pinkerton-deluxe-edition-death-to-false-metal/|website=pitchfork.com|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2007, Cuomo released ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'', a compilation of his demos recorded from 1992 to 2007.<ref name=\"drown\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.drownedinsound.com/articles/2494715|title=Weezer's Rivers Cuomo to release solo album|last=Kharas|first=Kev|magazine=[[Drowned in Sound]]|accessdate=October 16, 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017051234/http://drownedinsound.com/articles/2494715|archivedate=October 17, 2007 |url-status=live}}</ref> It was followed by ''[[Alone II: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' in November 2008<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/33865-rivers-cuomo-talks-alone-ii-weezer-that-hair/|title=Rivers Cuomo Talks Alone II, Weezer, That Hair|last=Thompson|first=Paul|date=October 28, 2007|website=|publisher=Pitchfork Media|accessdate=July 13, 2014}}</ref> and ''[[Alone III: The Pinkerton Years]]'' in November 2010; the latter album was sold exclusively with a book, ''The Pinkerton Diaries'', which collects Cuomo's writings from the preceding the release of ''Pinkerton''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/44605-rivers-cuomo-releasing-pinkerton-diaries-book-and-demos-comp-alone-iii/|title=Rivers Cuomo Releasing Pinkerton Diaries Book and Demos Comp Alone III|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|date=November 11, 2011|website=|publisher=Pitchfork Media|accessdate=July 13, 2014}}</ref>\n\nCuomo has made [[cameo appearance|cameos]] in a number of music videos. These include [[The Crystal Method]]'s \"Murder\" and the video for [[The Warlocks]]' \"Cocaine Blues.\" Cuomo also makes a guest appearance on [[Sugar Ray]]'s \"Boardwalk\", the first single on the group's latest album, ''[[Music for Cougars]]''. Cuomo featured on the song \"[[Magic (B.o.B song)|Magic]]\", on [[B.o.B]]'s debut album ''[[B.o.B Presents: The Adventures of Bobby Ray]]'' which was released in April 2010. In a May interview with [[HitQuarters]], producer-songwriter [[Lucas Secon]] confirmed that he had recently worked with Cuomo on both a [[Steve Aoki]] single and \"some Weezer stuff.\"<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_Lucas_Secon_Interview.html |title=Interview With Lucas Secon |publisher=[[HitQuarters]] |date=May 17, 2010 |accessdate=May 27, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120314062111/http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview%2Fopar%2Fintrview_Lucas_Secon_Interview.html |archivedate=March 14, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Cuomo collaborated with Japanese singer Hitomi for her first [[independent music|independent]] album ''[[Spirit (Hitomi album)|Spirit]]'', in the duet \"Rollin' with da Homies\", co-written by him. He was also featured on the [[Simple Plan]] song \"[[Can't Keep My Hands Off You]]\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Newman|first=Jason|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2011/03/31/simple-plan-rivers-cuomo-cant-keep-my-hands-off-you/|title=New Song: Simple Plan With Rivers Cuomo, 'Can't Keep My Hands Off You'|publisher=MTV|date=March 11, 2011|accessdate=January 27, 2013}}</ref> and [[Miranda Cosgrove]]'s song, \"High Maintenance\".<ref name=\"Graff-Billboard\">{{cite web|last1=Graff|first1=Gary|title=Miranda Cosgrove Taps Rivers Cuomo for 'High Maintenance' Duet|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/473348/miranda-cosgrove-taps-rivers-cuomo-for-high-maintenance-duet|website=Billboard|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> In 2013, Cuomo released a self-titled Japanese-language album with [[Scott Murphy (musician)|Scott Murphy]] of the band [[Allister]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.absolutepunk.net/showthread.php?t=2123462|title=Allister News |website=[[AbsolutePunk]]|date=January 13, 2011 |accessdate=January 14, 2011}}</ref> under the name [[Scott & Rivers]]. The album debuted at #1 on the iTunes Japan alternative charts. The album was released physically in Japan and digitally worldwide through [[iTunes]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/scott-rivers/id633593815 |title=iTunes - Music - Scott & Rivers by Scott & Rivers |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2013-03-20 |accessdate=2015-07-25}}</ref> In 2015, Cuomo appeared on the song \"Snowed In\" on [[Big Data (band)|Big Data's]] album ''[[2.0 (Big Data album)|2.0]]''.<ref name=\"Minsker-pf\">{{cite web|last1=Minsker|first1=Evan|title=Rivers Cuomo Teams With Big Data for \"Snowed In\"|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/58373-rivers-cuomo-teams-with-big-data-for-snowed-in/|website=pitchfork.com|accessdate=10 November 2016}}</ref> In the same year, Cuomo produced a [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] pilot for a sitcom based on his life, ''DeTour'', starring [[Ben Aldridge (actor)|Ben Aldridge]] as Cuomo. The pilot was not picked up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2015/07/tv-sitcom-about-rivers-cuomos-life-will-never-air/|title=TV sitcom about Rivers Cuomo's life will never air|date=2015-07-10|language=en-US|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Cuomo featured in RAC's \"I Still Wanna Know\", as well as Vic Mensa's \"Homewrecker\", which sampled Weezer's \"The Good Life\". The same year, he co-wrote and appeared on [[AJR (band)|AJR]]'s \"[[Sober Up]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weatherby|first1=Taylor|title=AJR Unveils 'Sober Up' Collaboration With Their Hero, Weezer's Rivers Cuomo: Premiere|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7824823/ajr-new-song-sober-up-rivers-cuomo-weezer-the-click|website=Billboard|accessdate=7 May 2018|date=6 August 2017}}</ref>  Cuomo also co-wrote the song \"Why Won't You Love Me\" on [[5 Seconds of Summer]]'s 2018 album [[Youngblood (5 Seconds of Summer album)|Youngblood]]. In 2018, he helped write two songs, \"Clock Work\" and \"Dancing Girl\" for [[Asian Kung-Fu Generation]]'s 2018 album, [[Hometown (Asian Kung-Fu Generation album)|Hometown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moshimoshi-nippon.jp/148583 |title=\nMMN Interview (Part 1): ASIAN KUNG-FU GENERATION discuss how writing 'Home Town' was different from their previous records |publisher=Moshi Moshi Nippon|date=2018-11-29 |accessdate=2018-11-29}}</ref> In 2019, he wrote and performed \"Backflip,\" the theme song for the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Green Eggs and Ham (TV series)|Green Eggs and Ham]]''.<ref>{{citeweb|last1=Ginsberg|first1=Gab|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/8541553/rivers-cuomo-backflip-netflix-green-eggs-ham|title=Get a First Listen Of Rivers Cuomo's 'Backflip' Theme Song For Netflix's 'Green Eggs and Ham': Exclusive|publisher=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=October 31, 2019|accessdate=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Artistry ==\n[[File:Weezer River Cuomo Bethlehem 2019 1.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Rivers Cuomo performing with Weezer at [[Musikfest]] in [[Bethlehem, Pennsylvania|Bethlehem]], [[Pennsylvania]] on August 5, 2019.]]\nAppearing on the [[Song Exploder]] podcast in 2016, Cuomo explained the process he used to write albums such as Weezer's ''[[Weezer (White Album)|White Album]]'' (2016). He maintains [[Spotify]] playlists of music with \"cool\" chord progressions that he uses to find musical inspiration. He sometimes uses piano to write vocal melodies his vocal muscles would be \"too lazy\" to create. Conversely, he improvises vocal melodies to write guitar solos, to avoid guitar habits and create solos \"you can sing along to\" with \"space in [them] because I have to breathe\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nTo write lyrics, Cuomo writes [[Stream of consciousness (narrative mode)|stream-of-consciousness]] thoughts in his journal, then highlights interesting lines and adds them to a spreadsheet of potential lyrics organized by number of syllables and [[Stress (linguistics)|strong-weak emphasis]]. When he comes to write a song, he finds lines that fit the melody and assembles them in a way that suggests a story.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2016/04/rivers-cuomo-weezer-summer-elaine-drunk-dori-song-exploder-podcast-stream/|title=Rivers Cuomo Explains His 'Crazy Way to Write' Tracks on 'Song Exploder' {{!}} SPIN|website=Spin|access-date=2016-04-20}}</ref> He rarely uses [[profanity]] in his lyrics, as \"Weezer came up at a time when [[Jane's Addiction]] released ''[[Nothing's Shocking]]''\u2014everyone was trying to be controversial. We looked back to rock and roll's pre-drug days\u2014to the clean images of the Beach Boys\u2014that felt, ironically, rebellious.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/features/rivers-cuomo-20080626|title=Q&A: Rivers Cuomo|last=Scaggs|first=Austin|date=2008-06-28|magazine=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2015-05-03}}</ref> He has experimented with various methods of \"concentration\", such as [[fasting]], to aid his songwriting.<ref name=\":0222\" />\n\n=== Influences ===\nCuomo credited the [[The Beach Boys|Beach Boys]] as a major influence on his early songwriting, and told ''Upset'' magazine:<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.upsetmagazine.com/features/weezer-interview-kings-of-the-world-white-album/|title=Weezer: Kings of the world {{!}} Interview {{!}} Upset|date=2016-05-06|language=en-US|access-date=2016-07-31}}</ref>{{cquote|I remember when I was 21 or 22, right when Weezer got together. I went to the local used record shop in Santa Monica with the intention of buying a classic album that was going to be a huge influence on me and my writing for Weezer. I flipped through all the records and I narrowed it down to two records. One of them was [[Led Zeppelin (album)|''Led Zeppelin'']], the other was ''[[Pet Sounds]]'' by the Beach Boys. It was almost a coin toss but I ended up going with ''Pet Sounds'', and I really came to love the melodies and the chord progression and the emotion on that record. It has to be one of the biggest influences right when Weezer was starting out.}}\n\nOn tour with Weezer following the ''Blue Album'', Cuomo listened extensively to the operas ''[[Aida]]'' (1871) and ''[[Madama Butterfly]]'' (1904), the rock opera ''[[Jesus Christ Superstar]]'' (1970), and the musical ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]]'' (1980), which influenced the composition of ''Pinkerton'' and the unreleased ''[[Songs from the Black Hole]].''<ref name=\"AloneII\">''Alone II: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo'' (liner notes). Rivers Cuomo. DGC, Interscope Records. 2008. B0012341-02</ref>\n\nOther influences include the [[the Beatles|Beatles]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]], [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]], [[Giacomo Puccini]], [[Green Day]], [[Jane's Addiction]], [[Cat Stevens]], [[Lou Barlow]], [[The Who]], [[Pixies (band)|Pixies]], [[Stevie Ray Vaughan]] and [[Sonic Youth]]. In the late 90s, Cuomo created an \"Encyclopedia of Pop\" for himself, a three-ring binder which examined pop and rock songs by artists including Nirvana, Green Day and [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]].<ref name=\"ELISCU\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/5933454/rivers_cuomos_encyclopedia_of_pop|title=Rivers Cuomo's Encyclopedia of Pop|last=Eliscu|first=Jenny|magazine=Rolling Stone|accessdate=2007-10-15}}</ref><ref name=\"page 270\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 270</ref> In 2008, he said his biggest recent inspiration had been [[Eminem]], praising his \"creativity, passion, inventiveness, and playfulness\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/features/interview/6773-rivers-cuomo/|title=Rivers Cuomo {{!}} Pitchfork|website=pitchfork.com|access-date=2016-08-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Voice ===\nCuomo possesses the vocal range of a tenor.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Kilby |first=Dylan |url= http://www.musicomh.com/reviews/albums/weezer-everything-will-alright-end |title= Weezer \u2013 Everything Will Be Alright In The End |date= 6 October 2014|accessdate= 16 January 2015 |magazine=musicOMH}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.axs.com/guy-grogan-channels-elliot-smith-and-rivers-cuomo-on-dynamite-bouquet-79926| title = Guy Grogan channels Elliot Smith and Rivers Cuomo on 'Dynamite Bouquet'| work=[[AXS (company)|AXS]]|date=29 March 2016|accessdate=13 May 2018| first=MacEagon| last=Voyce}}</ref><ref name=\"News\">{{cite news| url = http://www.newsadvance.com/the_burg/music/review-weezer-s-rivers-cuomo-has-reverse-engineered-a-really/article_1f7fca2b-8fc3-53b6-a5ac-a0be1bd1d18d.html| title = Review: Weezer's Rivers Cuomo has reverse engineered a really good album| work=[[Berkshire Hathaway]]|date=17 August 2016|accessdate=13 May 2018| first=Matt| last=Ashare}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://badgerherald.com/artsetc/2016/04/06/weezers-new-album-is-sonically-brilliant-but-lyrically-flawed/| title = Weezer's new album is sonically brilliant, but lyrically flawed| work=[[The Badger Herald]]|date=6 April 2016|accessdate=13 May 2018| first=Aaron| last=Reilly}}</ref> Matt Ashare of ''[[The News & Advance]]'' describes his voice as \"refreshingly pleasant\".<ref name=\"News\"/>\n\n==Equipment==\n[[Weezer (Blue Album)|The Blue Album]] was recorded with a [[Gibson Les Paul Special]] and a [[Fender Jaguar]], borrowed from producer [[Ric Ocasek]]. His amp was a vintage Mesa Boogie Mark I. For touring, he initially used a sonic blue Warmoth [[Fender Stratocaster]] copy with Seymour Duncan and DiMarzio pickups alongside Marshall amps. However, the guitar was destroyed in late 1997. In recent years, he has used additional Warmoth strat copies (in blue, seafoam green, black and blonde), as well as a [[Gibson SG]] painted in white with stock pickups. The guitars are plugged into a Kemper Profiler amp.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.musicradar.com/news/rig-tour-weezer|title=Rig tour: Weezer|last=Sharma|first=Amit|publisher=MusicRadar|accessdate=2018-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCuomo took a vow of [[sexual abstinence]] from 2004 until his marriage in 2006.<ref name=\":023\"/> On June 18, 2006, Cuomo married Kyoko Ito, whom he met in March 1997 at one of his solo concerts at the [[The Middle East (nightclub)|Middle East Club]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/2006/4/26/rivers-end-in-early-1995-a/|title=Rivers' End|last=Riesman|first=Abe J.|date=April 26, 2006|work=The Harvard Crimson}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Edwards|first=Gavin|date=November 12, 2009|title=Rivers Cuomo Grows Up (But Don't Worry, He's Still Kinda Weird)|journal=Rolling Stone|volume=|pages=60\u201363}}</ref> He proposed to her in Tokyo shortly before Christmas 2005.<ref name=\"HarvardCrim\">{{cite news |last=Chen |first=Lena |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=511290 |title=Hey, Rivers Cuomo! What did you do for Valentine's Day? |newspaper=[[The Harvard Crimson]] |date=2006-12-21 |accessdate=2007-10-17}}</ref> The wedding was held at a beach on Paradise Cove in [[Malibu, California|Malibu]] and was attended by all past and present members of Weezer (except for [[Mikey Welsh]]), as well as [[Kevin Ridel]] of [[Ridel High]] and [[Rick Rubin]].<ref name=shon>{{cite web|title=Full story|url=http://weezer.com/community/news_comment.asp?ParentAssetID=1455490&ArtistID=479&Start=&FullStory=Y&type=|publisher=Weezer.com|accessdate=9 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061129191804/http://www.weezer.com/community/news_comment.asp?ParentAssetID=1455490&ArtistID=479&Start=&FullStory=Y&type=|archivedate=29 November 2006}}</ref> The couple have two children: daughter Mia, born in 2007, and son Leo, born in 2011.\n\nCuomo was born with his [[Unequal leg length|left leg nearly two inches shorter than his right]]. After the success of ''[[Weezer (Blue Album)|The Blue Album]]'', Cuomo underwent the [[Ilizarov apparatus|Ilizarov procedure]] to correct the condition. This involved the surgical breaking of the bone in his leg, followed by several months of wearing a steel brace which required self-administered \"stretching\" of the leg four times daily; Cuomo likened the ordeal to \"crucifying [his] leg.\"<ref name=\":2\">Luerssen D., John, 2004 p. 148\u2013149</ref>\n\nCuomo has been vegetarian since childhood.<ref name=\"Rivers Cuomo Vegetarian\">{{cite web | url=http://www.happycow.net/famous/rivers_cuomo/|title=Rivers Cuomo Vegetarian |accessdate=2008-07-03 |publisher=Happycow.net}}</ref><ref name=\"Rivers 2002 Interview\">{{cite web|url=http://thebadpennyblog.com/2010/09/17/weezers-rivers-cuomo-in-2002-i-think-i-had-a-falling-out-with-the-fans/ |title=Weezer's Rivers Cuomo In 2002: 'I Think I Had A Falling Out With The Fans'|publisher=Thebadpennyblog.com |date=2010-09-17 |accessdate=2015-07-25}}</ref> However, in 2002, he told an interviewer that he might like to start eating meat regularly and claimed to have done so in the past, eating \"some kind of barbecued beef in Tokyo.\"<ref name=\"Rivers 2002 Interview\" />\n\nCuomo practices [[Vipassan\u0101]] [[meditation]] and was a student of [[S. N. Goenka]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.shambhalasun.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2850&Itemid=0 |title=Lion's Roar - Buddhist Wisdom for Our Time |publisher=Shambhalasun.com |date= |accessdate=2015-07-25}}</ref> As of mid-2009 he also teaches children's meditation as taught by S. N. Goenka.<ref>[http://www.vridhamma.org/en2009-08.aspx] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100713220221/http://www.vridhamma.org/en2009-08.aspx|date=July 13, 2010}}</ref> Cuomo helped acquire music rights and provided financial support to a 2007 documentary titled ''[[The Dhamma Brothers]]'' about [[Vipassan\u0101]] meditation being instituted in an Alabama state prison.<ref name=\"DBros\">{{cite web|url=http://www.frizzylogic.org/fl/2007/07/11/the-dhamma-brothers/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224182903/http://www.frizzylogic.org/fl/2007/07/11/the-dhamma-brothers/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2007-12-24 |title=The Dhamma Brothers |publisher=Frizzy Logic |accessdate=2007-10-15 }}</ref>\n\nCuomo is a soccer fan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://riverscuomo.com/bio/|title=Bio|date=2011-05-11|work=The Official Site of Rivers Cuomo -|access-date=2017-03-16|language=en-US}}</ref> In 2006, he wrote a song, \"My Day Is Coming\", in tribute to the [[United States men's national soccer team|U.S. men's soccer team]], and in 2010 wrote \"Represent\", an \"unofficial anthem\" for the U.S. team released as a Weezer single on June 11, the day before Team USA's [[2010 FIFA World Cup Group C#England vs United States|World Cup opener]] against [[England national football team|England]].<ref name=\"Represent\">{{cite news|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1641349/20100611/weezer.jhtml |title=Weezer Debut 'Unofficial' World Cup Song, 'Represent' |first=James |last=Montgomery |publisher=MTV.com |date=June 11, 2010 |accessdate=June 24, 2010}}</ref> In early 2008, Cuomo played in the [[Mia Hamm|Mia]] & [[Nomar Garciaparra|Nomar]] Celebrity Soccer Challenge and scored a goal in the game. The video for \"Lover in the Snow\", from the ''Alone'' album, deals with this game and his love of soccer.<ref name=\"Represent\" /> In August 2009, Cuomo participated in the Athletes for Africa 5v5 Charity Soccer Tournament in Toronto, Canada alongside actor [[Michael Cera]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/actor-takes-part-in-charity-soccer-tournament-today/article1201621/|title=Actor takes part in charity soccer tournament today|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Rafton|first=Robert|title=5v5 (7)|date=2009-08-22|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/rafton/3852145725/|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref>\n\nCuomo performed at a campaign rally for Democratic Presidential candidate [[Andrew Yang 2020 presidential campaign|Andrew Yang]] in Iowa on November 1, 2019, though Cuomo did not explicitly endorse Yang.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/11/rivers-cuomo-performs-weezer-songs-at-andrew-yang-yangapalooza-watch/|title=Here's Rivers Cuomo Performing at an Andrew Yang Rally in Iowa|date=2019-11-02|website=Spin|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/heres-what-happened-during-rivers-cuomos-yangapalooza-set/|title=Here\u2019s What Happened During Rivers Cuomo\u2019s Set at the Andrew Yang Rally in Iowa|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Rivers Cuomo discography}}\n\n'''With Weezer'''\n* [[Weezer (Blue Album)|''Blue Album'']] (1994)\n* [[Pinkerton (album)|''Pinkerton'']] (1996)\n* [[Weezer (Green Album)|''Green Album'']] (2001)\n* ''[[Maladroit]]'' (2002)\n* [[Make Believe (Weezer album)|''Make Believe'']] (2005)\n* [[Weezer (Red Album)|''Red Album'']] (2008)\n* ''[[Raditude]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Hurley (album)|Hurley]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Death to False Metal]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Everything Will Be Alright in the End]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Weezer (White Album)|White Album]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Pacific Daydream]]'' (2017)\n* ''[[Weezer (Teal Album)|Teal Album]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Weezer (Black Album)|Black Album]]'' (2019)\n* ''[[Van Weezer]]'' (2020)\n\n'''Solo''' \n* ''[[Alone: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[Alone II: The Home Recordings of Rivers Cuomo]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[Not Alone \u2013 Rivers Cuomo and Friends: Live at Fingerprints]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Alone III: The Pinkerton Years]]'' (2011)\n*''[[Scott & Rivers]]'' (2013)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.thecrimson.com/article.aspx?ref=513079 Interview with The Harvard Crimson about his Harvard years]\n* {{musicbrainz artist|name=Rivers Cuomo|id=87b6344f-c874-49ce-a8b3-e467ed6e05d0}}\n* {{IMDb name|1220530|Rivers Cuomo}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071223012636/http://community.livejournal.com/rivers_words/ Rivers Cuomo Archived MySpace Postings]\n* [http://goinginanewdirection.tripod.com/id10.html Rivers Cuomo on his creative career]\n* [http://www.shambhalasun.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=2850&Itemid=0 Biographical article in Shambhala Sun Magazine]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/ScottAndRivers/ Scott & Rivers on Facebook]\n\n{{Rivers Cuomo}}\n{{Weezer}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cuomo, Rivers}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American rock singers]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:Berklee College of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singers from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Singers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from California]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Weezer members]]\n[[Category:Musicians Institute alumni]]\n[[Category:Power pop musicians]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Connecticut]]\n", "name_user": "Owcschafer", "label": "safe", "comment": "rivers don't like soccer he said so in zoom call", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rivers_Cuomo"}
{"title_page": "South Slavs", "text_new": "{{specific|date=January 2016}} \n{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group            = South Slavs\n| image            = [[File:South Slavic Europe.svg|300px]]\n| caption          = {{leftlegend|#008080|South Slavic countries|outline=grey}}{{leftlegend|#808080|[[West Slavs|West]] and [[East Slavs|East Slavic]] countries|outline=grey}}\n| pop              = {{circa}} 30 million<ref>[https://joshuaproject.net/clusters/284 South Slavs]</ref>\n| regions          = [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]<br/>[[Bulgaria]]<br/>[[Croatia]]<br/>[[Montenegro]]<br/>[[North Macedonia]]<br/>[[Serbia]]<br/>[[Slovenia]]\n| langs            = [[Eastern South Slavic|East South Slavic languages:]]<br/>[[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]<br/>[[Macedonian language|Macedonian]]<br/>West South Slavic languages:<br/>[[Serbian language|Serbian]]<br/>[[Croatian language|Croatian]]<br/>[[Bosnian language|Bosnian]]<br/>[[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]]<br/>[[Slovenian language|Slovenian]]\n| rels             = [[Orthodox Christianity]]<br/>([[Bulgarians]], [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]], [[Montenegrins (ethnic group)|Montenegrins]] and [[Serbs]])<br/>[[Roman Catholicism]]<br/>([[Croats]] and [[Slovenes]])<br/>[[Islam]]<br/> ([[Bosniaks]], [[Pomaks]], [[Gorani people|Gorani]] and [[Torbe\u0161i]])\n| related          = Other [[Slavs]]\n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n}}\nThe '''South Slavs''' are a subgroup of [[Slavs|Slavic peoples]] who speak the [[South Slavic languages]]. They inhabit a contiguous region in the [[Balkans|Balkan Peninsula]] and the eastern [[Alps]], and in the modern era are geographically separated from the body of [[West Slavs|West Slavic]] and [[East Slavs|East Slavic]] people by the [[Romanians]], [[Hungarian people|Hungarians]], and [[Austrians]] in between. The South Slavs today include the nations of [[Bosniaks]], [[Bulgarians]], [[Croats]], [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]], [[Montenegrins (ethnic group)|Montenegrins]], [[Serbs]] and [[Slovenes]]. They are the main population of the [[Eastern Europe|Eastern]] and [[Southeastern Europe]]an countries of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Bulgaria]], [[Croatia]], [[Montenegro]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Serbia]], and [[Slovenia]].\n\nIn the 20th century, the country of [[Yugoslavia]] (lit. \"South Slavia\"/\"Southern Slavland\") united the regions inhabited by South Slavic nations{{spaced ndash}} with the key exception of [[Bulgaria]]{{spaced ndash}} into a single state. The concept of ''Yugoslavia'', a single state for all South Slavic peoples, emerged in the late 17th century and gained prominence through the 19th-century [[Illyrian movement]]. The [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]], renamed the Kingdom of Yugoslavia in 1929, was proclaimed on 1 December 1918, following the unification of the [[State of Slovenes, Croats and Serbs]] with the kingdoms of [[Kingdom of Serbia|Serbia]] and [[Kingdom of Montenegro|Montenegro]].\n\n==Terminology==\nThe South Slavs are known in Serbian, Macedonian and Montenegrin as ''Ju\u017eni Sloveni'' ({{cyrl|\u0408\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438 \u0421\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0438}}); in Bulgarian as ''Yuzhni Slavyani'' ({{cyrl|\u042e\u0436\u043d\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0438}}); in Croatian and Bosnian as ''Ju\u017eni Slaveni''; in Slovene as ''Ju\u017eni Slovani''. The Slavic root ''[[wikt:Reconstruction:Proto-Slavic/jug\u044a|*jug\u044a]]'' means \"south\". The [[Slavic ethnonym]] itself was used by 6th-century writers to describe the southern group of Early Slavs (the ''[[Sclaveni]]''); West Slavs were called ''[[Vistula Veneti|Veneti]]'' and East Slavs ''[[Antes (people)|Antes]]''.{{sfn|Kmietowicz|1976}} The South Slavs are also called \"Balkan Slavs\",<ref>{{harvnb|Kmietowicz|1976}}, {{harvnb|Vlasto|1970}}</ref> although this term does not encompass the Slovenes.\n\nAnother name popular in the early modern period was \"Illyrians\", the name of a pre-Slavic Balkan people, a name first adopted by Dalmatian intellectuals in the late 15th century to refer to South Slavic lands and population.{{sfn|URI|2000|p=104}} It was then used by the [[Habsburg Monarchy]], [[Illyrian Provinces|France]], and notably adopted by the 19th-century Croatian nationalist and Pan-Slavist [[Illyrian movement]].{{sfn|Hupchick|2002|p=199}} Eventually, the idea of [[Yugoslavism]] appeared, aimed at uniting all South Slav-populated territories into a common state. From this idea emerged [[Yugoslavia]], which however did not include [[Bulgaria]].\n\n==History==\n{{Hatnote|'Slavic invasion of the Balkans' redirects here.}}\n===Early South Slavs===\n {{main article|Early Slavs|Sclaveni}}\n\nThe Proto-Slavic [[Urheimat|homeland]] is the area of Slavic settlement in [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Eastern Europe]] during the first millennium AD, with its precise location debated by archaeologists, ethnographers and historians.<ref>{{harvnb|Kobyli\u0144ski|2005|pp=525\u2013526}}, {{harvnb|Barford|2001|p=37}}</ref> None of the proposed homelands reaches the [[Volga River]] in the east, over the [[Dinaric Alps]] in the southwest or the [[Balkan Mountains]] in the south, or past [[Bohemia]] in the west.<ref>{{harvnb|Kobyli\u0144ski|2005|p=526}}, {{harvnb|Barford|2001|p=332}}</ref> Traditionally, scholars put it in the marshes of Ukraine, or alternatively between the [[Bug River|Bug]] and the [[Dnieper]];{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=25}} however, according to F. Curta, the homeland of the southern Slavs mentioned by 6th-century writers was just north of the [[Lower Danube]].{{sfn|Curta|2006|p=56}} Little is known about the Slavs before the 5th century, when they began to spread out in all directions.\n\n[[Jordanes]], [[Procopius]] and other [[Late Antiquity|late Roman]] authors provide the probable earliest references to southern Slavs in the second half of the 6th century.{{sfn|Curta|2001|pp=71\u201373}} Procopius described the [[Sclaveni]] and [[Antes (people)|Antes]] as two barbarian peoples with the same institutions and customs since ancient times, not ruled by a single leader but living under democracy,<ref>{{harvnb|James|2014|p=95}}, {{harvnb|Kobyli\u0144ski|1995|p=524}}</ref> while Pseudo-Maurice called them a numerous people, undisciplined, unorganized and leaderless, who did not allow enslavement and conquest, and resistant to hardship, bearing all weathers.{{sfn|Kobyli\u0144ski|1995|pp=524\u2013525}} They were portrayed by Procopius as unusually tall and strong, of dark skin and \"reddish\" hair (neither [[blond]] nor [[black hair|black]]), leading a primitive life and living in scattered huts, often changing their residence.{{sfn|Kobyli\u0144ski|1995|p=524}} Procopius said they were [[henotheistic]], believing in the god of lightning ([[Perun]]), the ruler of all, to whom they sacrificed cattle.{{sfn|Kobyli\u0144ski|1995|p=524}} They went into battle on foot, charging straight at their enemy, armed with spears and small shields, but they did not wear armour.{{sfn|Kobyli\u0144ski|1995|p=524}}\n\nWhile archaeological evidence for a large-scale migration is lacking, most present-day historians claim that Slavs invaded and settled the Balkans in the 6th and 7th centuries.{{sfn|Fine|1991|pp=26\u201341}} According to this dominant narrative, up until the late 560s their main activity across the Danube was raiding, though with limited Slavic settlement mainly through Byzantine colonies of ''[[foederati]]''.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=29}} The [[Danube]] and [[Sava]] frontier was overwhelmed by large-scale Slavic settlement in the late 6th and early 7th century.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=33}} What is today [[central Serbia]] was an important geo-strategical province, through which the ''[[Via Militaris]]'' crossed.{{sfn|\u017divkovi\u0107|2002|p=187}} This area was frequently intruded upon by [[Barbarians in the Byzantine Empire|barbarians]] in the 5th and 6th centuries.{{sfn|\u017divkovi\u0107|2002|p=187}} From the Danube, the Slavs commenced raiding the Byzantine Empire on an annual basis from the 520s, spreading destruction, taking loot and herds of cattle, seizing prisoners and taking fortresses. Often, the Byzantine Empire was stretched, defending its rich Asian provinces from Arabs, Persians and others. This meant that even numerically small, disorganised early Slavic raids were capable of causing much disruption, but could not capture the larger, fortified cities.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=29}} The first Slavic raid south of the Danube was recorded by Procopius, who mentions an attack of the Antes, \"who dwell close to the Sclaveni\", probably in 518.<ref>{{harvnb|James|2014|p=95}}, {{harvnb|Curta|2001|p=75}}</ref> Sclaveni are first mentioned in the context of the military policy on the Danube frontier of Byzantine Emperor [[Justinian I]] (r. 527\u2013565).{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=76}} Throughout the century, Slavs raided and plundered deep into the Balkans, from Dalmatia to Greece and Thrace, and were also at times recruited as mercenaries, fighting the [[Ostrogoths]].{{sfn|Curta|2001|pp=78\u201386}} Justinian seems to have used the strategy of '[[Divide and rule|divide and conquer]]', and the Sclaveni and Antes are mentioned as fighting each other.{{sfn|James|2014|p=97}} The Antes are last mentioned as anti-Byzantine belligerents in 545, and the Sclaveni continued to raid the Balkans.<ref name=Byzantinoslavica-2003-78>{{cite book|title=Byzantinoslavica |volume=61\u201362 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=twwrAQAAIAAJ |year=2003 |publisher=Academia|pp=78\u201379}}</ref> In 558 the [[Avar Khaganate|Avars]] arrived at the Black Sea steppe, and defeated the Antes between the Dnieper and Dniester.{{sfn|Kobyli\u0144ski|1995|p=536}} The Avars subsequently allied themselves with the Sclaveni,{{sfn|Kobyli\u0144ski|1995|p=537\u2013539}} although there was an episode in which the Sclavene [[Daurentius]] (fl. 577\u2013579), the first Slavic chieftain recorded by name, dismissed Avar suzerainty and retorted that \"Others do not conquer our land, we conquer theirs [...] so it shall always be for us\", and had the Avar envoys slain.{{sfn|Curta|2001|pp=47, 91}} By the 580s, as the Slav communities on the Danube became larger and more organized, and as the Avars exerted their influence, raids became larger and resulted in permanent settlement. Most scholars consider the period of 581-584 as the beginning of large-scale Slavic settlement in the Balkans.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=31}} F. Curta points out that evidence of substantial Slavic presence does not appear before the 7th century and remains qualitatively different from the \"Slavic culture\" found north of the [[Danube]].{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=308}} In the mid-6th century, the Byzantines re-asserted their control of the Danube frontier, thereby reducing the economic value of Slavic raiding. This growing economic isolation, combined with external threats from the Avars and Byzantines, led to political and military mobilisation. Meanwhile, the itinerant form of agriculture (lacking [[crop rotation]]) may have encouraged micro-regional mobility. Seventh-century archaeological sites show earlier hamlet collections evolving into larger communities with differentiated zones for public feasts, craftmanship, etc.{{sfn|Curta|2007|p=61}} It has been suggested that the Sclaveni were the ancestors of the Serbo-Croatian group while the Antes were that of the [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgarian]] [[Seven Slavic tribes|Slavs]], with much mixture in the contact zones.<ref>{{harvnb|Hupchick|2004}}, {{harvnb|Fine|1991|p=26}}</ref> The diminished pre-Slavic inhabitants, also including also Romanized native peoples,{{Cref2|a}} fled from the barbarian invasions and sought refuge inside fortified cities and islands, whilst others fled to remote mountains and forests and adopted a [[transhumant]] lifestyle.{{sfn|Fine|1991|pp=37}} The Romance speakers within the fortified [[Dalmatian city-states]] managed to retain their culture and language for a long time.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=35}} Meanwhile, the numerous Slavs mixed with and assimilated the descendants of the indigenous population.{{sfn|Fine|1991|pp=38, 41}}\n\nSubsequent information about Slavs' interaction with the Greeks and early Slavic states comes from the 10th-century ''[[De Administrando Imperio]]'' (DAI) by Emperor [[Constantine VII Porphyrogenitus]], the 7th-century compilations of the ''[[Miracles of Saint Demetrius]]'' (MSD) and the ''History'' by [[Theophylact Simocatta]]. DAI mentions the beginnings of the Croatian, Serbian and Bulgarian states from the early 7th to the mid-10th century. MSD and Theophylact Simocatta mention the Slavic tribes in Thessaly and Macedonia at the beginning of the 7th century. The 9th-century ''[[Royal Frankish Annals]]'' (RFA) also mention Slavic tribes in contact with the [[Franks]].\n\n===Middle Ages===\n\nBy 700 AD, Slavs had settled in most of the Central and Southeast Europe, from Austria even down to the Peloponnese of Greece, and from the Adriatic to the Black Sea, with the exception of the coastal areas and certain mountainous regions of the Greek peninsula.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=36}} The [[Pannonian Avars|Avars]], who arrived in Europe in the late 550s and had a great impact in the Balkans, had from their base in the Carpathian plain, west of main Slavic settlements, asserted control over Slavic tribes with whom they besieged Roman cities. Their influence in the Balkans however diminished by the early 7th century and they were finally defeated and disappeared as a power at the turn of the 9th century by [[Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]] and the [[Frankish Empire]].{{sfn|Fine|1991|pp=29\u201343}} The first South Slavic polity and regional power was [[Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]], a state formed in 681 as a union between the much numerous [[Seven Slavic tribes|Slavic]] [[Sclaveni|tribes]] and the [[bulgars]] of [[Asparuh of Bulgaria|Khan Asparuh]]. The scattered Slavs in Greece, the ''Sklavinia'', were Hellenized.{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=41}} Romance-speakers lived within the fortified [[Dalmatian city-states]].{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=35}} Traditional historiography, based on DAI, holds that the migration of [[Serbs]] and [[Croats]] to the Balkans was part of a second Slavic wave, placed during Heraclius' reign.{{sfn|Curta|2001|p=66}}\n \nInhabiting the territory between the Franks in the north and Byzantium in the south, the Slavs were exposed to competing influences.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=90}} In 863 to Christianized [[Great Moravia]] were sent two Byzantine brothers monks [[Saints Cyril and Methodius]], Slavs from Thessaloniki on missionary work. They created the [[Glagolitic script]] and the first Slavic written language, [[Old Church Slavonic]], which they used to translate Biblical works. At the time, the West and South Slavs still spoke a similar language. The script used, [[Glagolitic]], was capable of representing all Slavic sounds, however, it was gradually replaced in Bulgaria in the 9th century, in Russia by the 11th century{{sfn|Portal|1969|pp=90\u201392}} Glagolitic survived into the 16th century in Croatia, used by Benedictines and Franciscans, but lost importance during the [[Counter-Reformation]] when Latin replaced it on the Dalmatian coast.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=92}} Cyril and Methodius' disciples found refuge in already [[Christianization of Bulgaria|Christian Bulgaria]], where the [[Old Church Slavonic]] became the ecclesiastical language.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=92}} [[Early Cyrillic alphabet]] was developed during the 9th century AD at the [[Preslav Literary School]] in [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]].<ref>{{cite book | first=Francis | last=Dvornik |title=The Slavs: Their Early History and Civilization | quote = The Psalter and the Book of Prophets were adapted or \"modernized\" with special regard to their use in Bulgarian churches, and it was in this school that glagolitic writing was replaced by the so-called Cyrillic writing, which was more akin to the Greek uncial, simplified matters considerably and is still used by the Orthodox Slavs. | year=1956 |place=Boston | publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences |page=179}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/southeasterneuro0000curt |url-access=registration |quote=Cyrillic preslav. |title=Southeastern Europe in the Middle Ages, 500\u20131250|series=Cambridge Medieval Textbooks|author= Florin Curta|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2006|isbn=978-0521815390|pages= [https://archive.org/details/southeasterneuro0000curt/page/221 221]\u2013222}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/?id=J-H9BTVHKRMC&pg=PR3-IA34&lpg=PR3-IA34&dq=The+Orthodox+Church+in+the+Byzantine+Empire+Cyrillic+preslav+eastern#v=onepage&q=%20preslav%20eastern&f=false|chapter= The Orthodox Church in the Byzantine Empire|title=Oxford History of the Christian Church|author= J. M. Hussey, Andrew Louth|publisher= Oxford University Press|year= 2010|isbn=978-0191614880|pages= 100}}</ref> The earliest Slavic literary works were composed in [[Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]], [[Duklja]] and Dalmatia. The religious works were almost exclusively translations, from Latin (Croatia, Slovenia) and especially Greek (Bulgaria, Serbia).{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=92}} In the 10th and 11th centuries the [[Old Church Slavonic]] leaded to the creation of various regional forms like [[Serbo-Croatian]] and [[Slovene language|Slovenian]]{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=92}} Economic, religious and political centres of [[Ohrid]] and [[Plovdiv]] contributed to the important [[Ohrid Literary School|literary production]] in the [[Bulgarian Empire]].{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=93}} The [[Bogomil]] sect, derived from Manichaeism, was deemed heretical, but managed to spread from [[First Bulgarian Empire|Bulgaria]] to Bosnia (where it gained a foothold).{{sfn|Portal|1969|pp=93\u201395}} and France ([[Cathars]]).\n\n[[Carantania|Carinthia]] came under Germanic rule in the 10th century and came permanently under Western (Roman) Christian sphere of influence.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=96}} What is today Croatia came under Eastern Roman (Byzantine) rule after the Barbarian age, and while most of the territory was Slavicized, a handful of fortified towns, with mixed population, remained under Byzantine authority and continued to use Latin.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=96}} Dalmatia, now applied to the narrow strip with Byzantine towns, came under the Patriarchate of Constantinople, while the Croatian state remained pagan until Christianization during the reign of [[Charlemagne]], after which religious allegiance was to Rome.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=96}} Croats threw off Frankish rule in the 9th century, and took over the Byzantine Dalmatian towns, after which Hungarian conquest led to Hungarian suzerainty, although retaining an army and institutions.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=96\u201397}} Croatia lost much of Dalmatia to the Republic of Venice which held it until the 18th century.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=97}} Hungary governed Croatia through a duke, and the coastal towns through a ''[[Ban of Croatia|ban]]''.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=97}} A feudal class emerged in the Croatian hinterland in the late 13th century, among whom were the [[Kurjakovi\u0107]], [[Ka\u010di\u0107]] and most notably the [[\u0160ubi\u0107]].{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=97\u201398}} Dalmatian fortified towns meanwhile maintained autonomy, with a Roman patrician class and Slavic lower class, first under Hungary and then Venice after centuries of struggle.{{sfn|Portal|1969|p=98}}\n\n[[Ibn al-Faqih]] described two kinds of South Slavic people, the first of swarthy complexion and dark hair, living near the Adriatic coast, and the other as light, living in the hinterland.{{cn|date=March 2018}}\n\n===Early modern period===\n \nAfter Ottoman expansion into Byzantine territories in the east in the first half of the 14th century, the internally divided [[Second Bulgarian Empire|Bulgarian Empire]] and the short-lived and [[Fall of the Serbian Empire|crumbling]] [[Serbian Empire]] stood next. In 1371, the Ottomans defeated a large Serbian army at the [[Battle of Maritsa]], and in 1389 defeated the Serbian army at the [[Battle of Kosovo]]. By now, Serbian and Bulgarian rulers became Ottoman vassals, the southern Serbian provinces and Bulgaria holding out until annexation in the 1390s. The Ottomans conquered Constantinople (1453), Greece (1453\u201360), the [[Serbian Despotate]] (1459) and [[Kingdom of Bosnia|Bosnia]] (1463). Much of the Balkans was under Ottoman rule throughout the [[early modern period]]. Ottoman rule lasted from the 14th into the early 20th century in some territories. Ottoman society was multi-ethnic and multi-religious, and confessional groups were divided according to the [[Millet (Ottoman Empire)|''millet'' system]], in which Orthodox Christians (Greeks, Bulgarians, Serbs, etc.) constituted the [[Rum Millet]]. In Islamic jurisprudence, the Christians had ''[[dhimmi]]'' status, which entailed certain taxes and lesser rights. Through Islamization, communities of [[Slavic Muslims]] emerged, which survive until today in Bosnia, south Serbia, North Macedonia, and Bulgaria. \n\nIn the 16th century, the [[Habsburg Monarchy]] controlled what is today Slovenia, Croatia and northern Serbia. The [[Kingdom of Croatia (Habsburg)|Kingdom of Croatia]], which included smaller parts of what is today Croatia, was a crown land of the Habsburg emperor. The early modern period saw large-scale migrations of Orthodox Slavs (mainly Serbs) to the north and west. The [[Military Frontier]] was set up as the ''[[cordon sanitaire]]'' against Ottoman incursions. There were several rebellions against Ottoman rule, but it was not until the 18th century that parts of the Balkans, namely [[Habsburg-occupied Serbia (1788\u201392)|Serbia, were liberated]] for a longer period. While [[Pan-Slavism]] has its origins in the 17th-century Slavic Catholic clergymen in the Republic of Venice and Republic of Ragusa, it crystallized only in the mid-19th century amidst rise of nationalism in the Ottoman and Habsburg empires.\n\n==Statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"5\" style=\"margin:auto;\"\n|-\n! Countries\n! [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]]\n! [[Bulgaria]]\n! [[Croatia]]\n! [[Montenegro]]\n! [[North Macedonia]]\n! [[Serbia]]\n! [[Slovenia]]\n|-\n! Flag\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Bosnia and Herzegovina|size=50px}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Bulgaria|size=50px}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Croatia|size=50px}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Montenegro|size=50px}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|North Macedonia|size=50px}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Serbia|size=50px}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Flagicon|Slovenia|size=50px}}\n|-\n! Coat of arms\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Coat of arms|Bosnia and Herzegovina|size=50px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Coat of arms|Bulgaria|size=50px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Coat of arms|Croatia|size=50px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Coat of arms|Montenegro|size=50px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Coat of arms|North Macedonia|size=50px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Coat of arms|Serbia|size=50px|text=none}}\n| style=\"text-align:center\" | {{Coat of arms|Slovenia|size=50px|text=none}}\n|-\n! Capital\n| [[Sarajevo]]\n| [[Sofia]]\n| [[Zagreb]]\n| [[Podgorica]]\n| [[Skopje]]\n| [[Belgrade]]\n| [[Ljubljana]]\n|-\n! Independence\n| March 1,<br /> 1992\n| October 5,<br /> 1908\n| June 25,<br /> 1991\n| June 3,<br /> 2006\n| September 8,<br /> 1991\n| July 13,<br /> 1878\n| June 25,<br /> 1991\n|-\n! Current President\n| [[\u0160efik D\u017eaferovi\u0107]]\n| [[Rumen Radev]]\n|[[Zoran Milanovi\u0107]]\n| [[Milo \u0110ukanovi\u0107]]\n| [[Stevo Pendarovski]]\n| [[Aleksandar Vu\u010di\u0107]]\n| [[Borut Pahor]]\n|-\n! Current Prime Minister\n| [[Denis Zvizdi\u0107]]\n| [[Boyko Borisov]]\n| [[Andrej Plenkovi\u0107]]\n| [[Du\u0161ko Markovi\u0107]]\n|